BSE: Spain, first cases in Andalucia (edited)
--------------------------------------------
The Laboratory of Animal Health in Cordoba detected the first 2 cases of
bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) in Andalucia, southern Spain. The
animals, aged 5 and 11 years, were from 2 different farms. They were
slaughtered because they tested positive for tuberculosis; no clinical
signs of BSE were detected. [All movement of their herds, a total of 305
animals, has been restricted. So far 5788 animals have been tested under
the regional surveillance programme and 11.407 tonnes of concentrates of
animal origin have been given to the authorities by the food industry.
A total of 45 cases of BSE have been reported throughout Spain since
November 2000; 34 of them in the north west of the country. Galicia, with
common borders and a long tradition of commerce with Portugal (country that
shares with Ireland the second highest national case tally), registers 21
cases. The neighboring regions Castilla-Leon and Asturias follow with 9 and
4 cases [respectively. The disease has also been detected in Navarra (5),
Pais Vasco (1), Catalunya (2), Baleares (2), and Castilla-La Mancha (1).
The breeds affected are varied: Holstein-Fresian (26), mixed (12) Parda
Alpina (2), Pirenaica (2), Rubia Gallega (1), Limousine (1), and Fleckvich (1).
