Source: M2 Communications Ltd. [edited

Danish authorities should have investigated possible BSE cases in 1995 - claim
--------------------------------------------------
The Danish authorities have been criticised for doing nothing to protect
the public despite the fact that BSE was probably in Denmark in 1995. Irish
authorities found a Danish-born cow with BSE in 1995, according to
Politiken, a Danish newspaper.
As the cow had only been in Ireland for 26 weeks, it appears likely that it
was infected in Denmark, experts say. According to the newspaper, the
Danish authorities did not investigate where the farm the cow originated
from got the fodder and if there were any more infected animals in the
country. Proof of the existence of BSE in Denmark would have been likely to
have had a great impact on the export of Danish beef.
